# HTML heading structure (h1–h6)

- **Use headings for structure, not styling**: don’t pick `<h*>` just to get bigger text; use CSS for visual size.
- **One `<h1>` per page/view**: the main page title should be the only `<h1>` in a screen/route.
- **Don’t skip levels**: after `<h1>`, use `<h2>` for top-level sections, then `<h3>` for subsections, etc.
- **Keep headings ordered**: avoid jumping back and forth (e.g. `<h2>` → `<h4>` → `<h2>`), unless a deliberate nested structure exists.
- **Prefer real headings over generic tags**: use `<h2>` instead of `<div className="heading">` when the text is a section heading.

## Examples (React / JSX)

```jsx
// ❌ BAD: multiple h1, skipped level
export function ProductPage() {
  return (
    <>
      <h1>Products</h1>
      <h1>On sale</h1>
      <h3>Shipping</h3>
    </>
  );
}
```

```jsx
// ✅ GOOD: single h1, consistent hierarchy
export function ProductPage() {
  return (
    <>
      <h1>Products</h1>
      <h2>On sale</h2>
      <h2>Shipping</h2>
      <h3>International</h3>
    </>
  );
}
```
